ic Body in Digital Migration Studies -- t9. Queer Digital Migration Research: Two Case Studies -- tSection IV Visuality and Digital Media -- tIntroduction to Section IV: Visuality and Digital Media -- t10. Migrant Agency and Platformed Belongings: The Case of TikTok -- t11. Affective Performances of Rooted Cosmopolitanism Through Facebook During the Festival International de Folklore et de Percussion in Louga, Senegal -- t12. Situating the Body in Digital Migration Research : Embodied Methodologies for Analysing Virtual Reality Films on Displacement -- tSection V Datafication, Infrastructuring and Securitization -- tIntroduction to Section V : Datafication, Infrastructuring and Securitization -- t13. The Weaponization of Datafied Sound : The Case of Voice Biometrics in German Asylum Procedures -- t14. McKinsey Consultants and Technocratic Fantasies : Crafting the Illusion of Orderly Migration Management in Greece -- t15. Undocumented and Datafied: Anticipation, Borders and Everyday Life -- tSection VI Conclusions -- tConclusions: On Doing Digital Migration Studies -- tIndex0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2fd2star  aDoing Digital Migration present a comprehensive entry point to the variety of theoretical debates, methodological interventions, political discussions and ethical debates around migrant forms of belonging as articulated through digital practices. Digital technologies impact upon everyday migrant lives, while vice versa migrants play a key role in technological developments - be it when negotiating the communicative affordances of platforms and devices, as consumers of particular commercial services such as sending remittances, as platform gig workers or test cases for new advanced surveillance technologies. With its international scope, this anthology invites scholars to pluralize understandings of 'the migrant' and 'the digital'. The anthology is organized in five different sections: Creative Practices; Digital Diasporas and Placemaking; Affect and Belonging; Visuality and digital media and Datafication, Infrastructuring, and Securitization. These sections are dedicated to emerging key topics and debates in digital migration studies, and sections are each introduced by international experts.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 4aDigital and Social Media. 4aFilm, Media, and Communication. 4aGender and Sexuality Studies. 4aMedia Studies. 4aScience and Technology. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Emigration & Immigration.2bisacsh  aMigration, belonging, digital practices, digital migration studies, diaspora.1 aAiello, Giorgia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAlencar, Amanda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAsadchy, Yan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBaldassar, Loretta, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBayramoğlu, Yener, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCosta, Elisabetta, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDenić, Nadica, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGhislain, Bahati, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGodin, Marie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHorsti, Karina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJaramillo-Dent, Daniela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKaratzogianni, Athina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeurs, Koen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeu